<section class="section section--alt" id="qb-help-reports-wrong-definition">
  <div class="container container--narrow">
    <header class="section__header">
      <p class="section__eyebrow">In plain terms</p>
      <h2 class="section__heading">&ldquo;Reports show wrong numbers,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    </header>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A QuickBooks report &mdash; the Profit &amp; Loss, the balance sheet, the A/R or A/P aging, a sales-by-customer summary &mdash; is just a view of the transactions already in your file, filtered and grouped by the settings you choose. When people say the report &ldquo;shows wrong numbers,&rdquo; they usually mean one of a few things: the totals don&rsquo;t match what they expect or know to be true; the report won&rsquo;t <em>tie out</em> to the bank statements or source documents; income or expenses look far too high or too low; or two reports that should agree (say, the balance sheet and the bank balance) don&rsquo;t.</p>
      <p>The good news is that most of these trace to a short list of causes, and the self-fix steps below address them in order of likelihood &mdash; setting the right basis, date range, and filters, then cleaning up uncategorized transactions, clears a large share of cases. What the steps <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fully fix is months of miscategorized or duplicated transactions and a reconciliation that no longer ties &mdash; that&rsquo;s bookkeeping repair, not a report setting. And if the underlying issue is genuinely an Intuit account or a software bug, that&rsquo;s Intuit&rsquo;s to resolve &mdash; but report <em>accuracy</em> almost always lives in the books, which is our work.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

